en mother and daughter when Poppy becomes involved with a Métis lover. This novel expands the patriarchal canon of Canadian prairie fiction by depicting the agency of a successful female settler and, as noted by Dorothy Livesay, was “one of the first, if not the first Canadian novel wherein the plight of the Native Indian and the Métis is honestly and painfully recorded.” The afterword by Carole Gerson and Janice Dowson provides substantial information about author Christine van der Mark and situates her under-acknowledged book within the contexts of Canadian social, literary, and publishing history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFiction. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAlberta literature.  aCanadian fiction.  aCanadian women writers.  aGreat Depression.  aIndigenous communities.  aMétis in Canadian literature.  aNorthern literature.  afemale protagonists.  amodernism.  arural communities.1 aDowson, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerson, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112072240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771120722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771120722/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles